    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Unscrewing the handle is a good start, but before you dive into the pipes, it's wise to check the washer and the gasket or O-ring. These are usually located behind the handle or in the valve seat. When you remove the handle, make sure to carefully disassemble the valve stem and take note of the order in which the parts are arranged. This will make reassembly easier later on. Keep an eye out for any signs of wear or damage on the washer and gasket. If they're worn out, you'll need to replace them. Remember, a new washer might not be enough if the gasket or O-ring is also worn out. And don't forget to clean the valve seat before installing the new washer. Good luck, and don't let the sink overflow!",
